20th(Old Bowery Bay) Road, north side, east of 33rd Street, showing at the left foreground the home of George Kouwenhoven. At the right (center of view) is shown the family burial place of the Lawrence and Leverich families. In the background is the home of Peter Luyster. The owner of this farm was William Lawrence from 1700-1732. He was followed by John Leverich in 1732, and William Leverich later, who had possession until 1754. George Kouwenhoven was the owner from 1852-1860. Francis Durye Kouwenhoven erected (or remodeled?) this house in 1857. Harry Puschea Williams who married into the Kouwenhoven family is the present owner of the house. This house, seen in a set of four views, was no longer standing in May 1929.

May 1923.
Views 1 & 4.
View 2: 1922.
View 3: March 1923.

Eugene L. Ambruster Collection.

20th (Old Bowery Bay) Road (along front of Geo. Kouwenhoven house seen at left), between 33rd and 36th Streets. This is a rear view of the Lawrence family's private cemetery taken from 21st Ave. Eventually it will be removed because it is in the direct line of the extension of 35th Street. In the background are the Steinway and Sons piano and foundry factories.

Eugene L. Ambruster Collection.

(2)

The same, at another angle.

Arthur White.

1927?

33rd Street, north from 20th Road toward the East River waterfront industrial area. The garage (left) is at the S.W. corner of 20th Avenue. The Dietz coal silo is on a canal at 19th Avenue, and to its right is the Steinway piano factory.

P. L. Sperr
June 3, 1927
